{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17614072","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17614072"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T14:41:09+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T14:41:09+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16338"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"16338","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/16338"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.05,0,0,0.89,0.05]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9029"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"116456"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"9029","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/9029"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16338"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"98455"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4941"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"4946"},{"type":"tags","id":"5586"},{"type":"tags","id":"7519"},{"type":"tags","id":"7527"},{"type":"tags","id":"7531"},{"type":"tags","id":"10416"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"21477"},{"type":"contributions","id":"21483"},{"type":"contributions","id":"22746"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"116456","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/116456"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EThe retina contains specialised regions that are essential for different aspects of vision. One such region is the macula lutea (or fovea).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes its primary function?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Provides peripheral vision","Controls pupillary light reflexes","Detects motion in low light conditions","Enables high-acuity central vision","Processes colour vision in the periphery"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Emacula lutea enables high-acuity central vision\u003C/strong\u003E through its dense concentration of cone photoreceptors, particularly in its central region called the fovea centralis. This area is specialised for detailed vision tasks like reading and facial recognition.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EProviding peripheral vision\u003C/strong\u003E is actually the function of the peripheral retina, which contains mainly rod photoreceptors. \u003Cstrong\u003EDetecting motion in low light conditions\u003C/strong\u003E is primarily accomplished by rod photoreceptors in the peripheral retina. \u003Cstrong\u003EProcessing colour vision in the periphery\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect as colour vision is primarily processed in the macula where cone density is highest. \u003Cstrong\u003EControlling pupillary light reflexes\u003C/strong\u003E is a function of the retinal ganglion cells that project to the pretectal nuclei, not specifically the macula.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe macula appears yellow (lutea) due to the presence of xanthophyll pigments that protect the retina from harmful blue light. Its central 1.5 mm contains the highest density of cone photoreceptors in the retina, making it crucial for detailed vision.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["The macula lutea contains the highest concentration of cone photoreceptors in the retina and is responsible for high-acuity central vision.","The fovea centralis, located at the center of the macula, provides the sharpest visual acuity due to its cone-only composition."],"references":["Michael-Titus, A. T., \u0026 Shortland, P. (2022). The Nervous System, E-Book: The Nervous System, E-Book. Elsevier Health 